<br>
My plane was diverted to Vancouver, and those of us on the plane didn't know about the tragedy until after we landed.  Hundreds of people walked off of planes in Vancouver...alive, we were the lucky ones.  I saw grown men bawling like babies.  Strangers held each other, people kindly offered cell phones, people opened their homes to those stranded so far from home.  I was so lucky, so very lucky.  John was able to drive the three hours to come get me that night and I made it home safely, unlike others that day, who never came home.<br>
<br>
I travel a lot with my job, so the thought of someone ramming a plane of people into a tower is so incredibly horrifying I can barely stand to think of it.  <br>
<br>
If you think that little joke is so damn funny and that everyone should shake off the sadness of the tragic events of 9-11, why don't you find a widow, or someone who lost a loved one, someone who burned to death, or was vaporized or who maybe died slowly, crushed in the rubble too far from rescue, and tell them the joke.  It's funny, right? <p><a href="http://www.saraquael.com/gloriana.html"><img src="http://fyd.fuxored.net/glorymedium.jpg" border="0"></a><p>
